SUVAT4

The Kinematic Equation for Final Velocity as a Function of Distance for Constant Acceleration

For an object under constant acceleration, the square of the object's final velocity is equal to the square of its initial velocity plus two times the acceleration times the distance travelled.

v^{2} = u^{2} + 2as

where:

v [var. scal. FinalVelocity, L T^{-1}, m s^{-1}] is the final velocity of the object
u [var. scal. InitialVelocity, L T^{-1}, m s^{-1}] is the initial velocity of the object
a [const. scal. Acceleration, L T^{-2}, m s^{-2}] is the acceleration of the object
s [var. scal. Distance, L, m] is the distance travelled by the object

